    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cbe44239_027ab262",
        "filename": "golden/modules/byblameentry-sk/byblameentry-sk.js",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 10009
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-19T21:28:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Why do this just for \u003csmall\u003e? What about all the other elements that we don\u0027t style explicitly?\n\nNormally the way to deal with browser inconsistencies is to include a set of styles in a top level style sheet (e.g. that of gold-scaffold-sk, which is included in all Gold pages) that will either normalize differences across user agent styles[1], or simply reset default styles altogether[2] and overwrite them with your own.\n\nAFAIU we don\u0027t currently do this, so unless \u003csmall\u003e is obviously broken across browsers, I\u0027d say let\u0027s continue to rely on the user agent styles like we do for many other elements.\n\nBut I agree that consistency across browsers is an important goal. At some point we should think carefully about how to normalize all our styles across browsers at the application level (i.e. Gold).\n\nPlease let me know what you think.\n\n[1] Example: https://github.com/necolas/normalize.css/blob/master/normalize.css\n[2] Example: https://meyerweb.com/eric/tools/css/reset/",
      "parentUuid": "f239eab9_5944bc93",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 41,
        "startChar": 23,
        "endLine": 41,
        "endChar": 28
      },
      "revId": "37704ea28ca3f3149d03a5193ee58e7ca701f435",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
